    "howmade": "Vellum was made by soaking a freshly skinned calf or sheep hide in a lime solution for several days to loosen the hair, then stretching it tightly on a wooden frame and scraping both sides repeatedly with a curved blade while still wet — this removed all fat, hair, and uneven thickness. As it dried under tension, it became almost translucent, smooth, and rigid. One Bible required approximately 250 animal skins. Quills were plucked from the wing of a living goose (the wing's natural curve made them comfortable to hold), hardened by pushing into hot sand, then cut to a fine nib with a small knife — the origin of the term 'penknife.' Iron gall ink was made by crushing oak galls (small balls formed on oak trees by wasp larvae), boiling them in water, then adding iron sulfate and gum arabic. The ink was initially pale but darkened as it oxidized, eventually biting into the vellum surface — which is why it has survived 1,000+ years. Tally sticks required no special preparation: a fresh hazel rod was notched (a large V-cut = £1, a smaller cut = a shilling, a thin line = a penny), then split cleanly down the middle with a knife.",
    "who": "<b>Monastic scribe</b> — a monk working in the scriptorium (monastery writing room), the primary preserver of literacy and record-keeping in early medieval Europe. <b>Royal steward / bailiff</b> — managed the lord's estates and tax collection with simple written accounts. <b>Church treasurer</b> — the Catholic Church was the most sophisticated financial institution of the Middle Ages, managing vast properties across all of Europe. For common people: any two parties to a debt used tally sticks — no literacy required, no professional involved.",
