    "solution": "The double-entry bookkeeping system: every transaction creates two entries — a <b>Debit</b> (left side) and a <b>Credit</b> (right side) that must always equal each other. This self-checking mechanism meant errors and fraud were detectable automatically. The system used two books: the <b>Journal</b> (transactions recorded chronologically as they happened) and the <b>Ledger</b> (the same transactions reorganized by account). Periodically, a <b>Trial Balance</b> confirmed all debits equaled all credits — if they didn't, something was wrong. Luca Pacioli's 1494 book <em>Summa de Arithmetica</em> codified this system in print for the first time, spreading it across Europe.",
