    "howmade": "Paper in Renaissance Italy was made from discarded linen rags — old clothing and linens collected by rag-and-bone men across the city. The rags were soaked in water for weeks until they decomposed into pulp, then beaten further in water-powered stamping mills. The pulp was scooped onto a wire mesh frame, shaken to distribute it evenly, then pressed between felt sheets and hung to dry. The result was a strong, smooth sheet far cheaper than vellum. Ledger books were assembled by folding sheets in half, sewing them into gatherings, and binding them between thick wooden boards covered in leather. Bookbinders ruled the pages by pressing a pointed bone tool along a straightedge, creating the straight lines that divided debit and credit columns — every line drawn by hand before a single transaction was recorded.",
