    "idea": "Two parallel ideas: First — what if a machine could print text faster and more legibly than handwriting, with carbon copies for duplicates? Second — what if accountants organized into a licensed profession with formal examinations, ethical codes, and legal accountability — like doctors or lawyers?",
    "solution": "The <b>typewriter</b> (Remington No. 1, 1874) mechanized document production. Financial statements, invoices, and correspondence could now be typed faster, more legibly, and with simultaneous carbon copies. The <b>professional accounting body</b> emerged: the Institute of Chartered Accountants in Scotland (ICAS, 1854) — the world's first — followed by the American Association of Public Accountants (1887). The CPA and CA designations were born, giving accounting the same professional status as law and medicine.",
