    "howmade": "The Remington No. 1 typewriter was built in a sewing machine factory — Remington & Sons, who made guns and sewing machines, were the first mass manufacturers. Each key was attached to a type bar with the letter cast in reverse relief at the tip; striking a key caused the bar to swing up and hit an inked ribbon pressed against the paper, transferring the letter. The mechanism was entirely mechanical — no electricity required. Carbon copy paper was made industrially by machine-coating paper with a precise layer of carbon pigment in wax — standardized manufacturing meant consistent copy quality. Fountain pens used a rubber sac that compressed when squeezed to fill with ink through the nib, replacing the need to dip into an inkwell every few seconds — a dramatic improvement for high-volume writing.",
    "who": "<b>Chartered Accountant (CA)</b> — created by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in Scotland (ICAS, Edinburgh, 1854) — the world's first professional accounting designation. <b>Certified Public Accountant (CPA)</b> — American equivalent; the AICPA's predecessor was founded 1887. <b>Auditor</b> — emerged as a distinct role, hired by shareholders to independently verify company accounts. <b>Female clerks and typists</b> — the typewriter brought women into accounting offices for the first time at scale; typewriting was marketed toward women because men considered it beneath them, permanently changing the demographic of the bookkeeping profession.",
    "impact": "Accounting became a licensed, legally accountable profession — comparable in status to law and medicine. The audit became a standard requirement for public companies, creating the trust infrastructure that made modern stock markets possible. The typewriter accelerated document production and introduced the carbon copy — for the first time, a transaction could be recorded in triplicate simultaneously.",
    "limit": "Even with typewriters, adding up columns of numbers was still done entirely by hand — a clerk totaling a 500-row payroll column took many minutes and inevitably made errors. Verifying the total meant doing it again from scratch. As banks and large companies processed tens of thousands of transactions per day, arithmetic was the final remaining manual bottleneck. What was needed was a machine that could perform addition automatically."
